    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, return a compact summary (keep each list <=20 entries):\n1) total row count; 2) min(timestamp) and max(timestamp); 3) unique cmdb_id values (up to 20); 4) unique KPI/trace/log name values (for metric.csv use kpi_name, for trace.csv use trace_name, for log.csv use log_name) up to 20; 5) top 20 most frequent (cmdb_id, KPI/trace/log name) pairs with their counts (for error_logs.csv, show top 20 message texts with counts instead of KPI names). Keep the output concise and tabular (columns: key,value). Do not return full raw rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the prior telemetry summary we know: metric, trace, and log data are concentrated in 2022-03-21 11:00–11:29 CST; metrics and traces show heavy activity from adservice and shippingservice pods; error_logs are dominated by a large number of frontend warnings (~1616/1708), with a smaller set of errors (~47) and a few HTTP 500s. This gives an initial view but no root-cause localization yet. Next we must perform preprocessing: compute global thresholds for each component-KPI time series (metrics and logs) so we can detect anomalies inside the incident window. We should therefore aggregate metric.csv by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and log.csv by (cmdb_id, log_name) and compute global statistics (count, P95, min, max) for each series, returning a compact top-20 summary to narrow candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and log.csv. For metric.csv: group by (cmdb_id,kpi_name) and compute for each group: count, global P95 of value, min(value), max(value). Return the top 20 groups ordered by count (columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, p95, min, max). For log.csv: group by (cmdb_id,log_name) and compute count, global P95 of value, min(value), max(value); return the top 20 groups ordered by count (columns: cmdb_id, log_name, count, p95, min, max). Keep outputs compact (<=20 rows each). Do not print full raw time series." }

{
    "analysis": "We have global summaries and group-level P95 thresholds for metric and log series (each group has 30 samples across the 11:00–11:29 window). The metric groups of interest that stand out are shippingservice2-0 (a mesh.source series with very large values) and many adservice KPI series. Error logs are dominated by frontend warnings (~1616 entries) and a small set of real errors (~47) including a few HTTP 500s. To localize the two failures we must now detect actual anomalies inside the incident window using the global thresholds (P95) computed on the full series for each component-KPI, then find which component-KPIs show consecutive anomalies and their first anomaly timestamps. This will narrow candidate components and times for further trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) group compute the global P95 of value using the full series (no filtering). Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2022-03-21 11:00:00 CST through 2022-03-21 11:30:00 CST (inclusive) and mark points where value > global P95. For each group that has at least one anomalous point, compute: anomaly_count (number of points > P95 in the window), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first timestamp in the window where value > P95), and max_consecutive_anomalies (longest run of consecutive minutes with value > P95). Return the top 20 groups ordered by anomaly_count (columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_consecutive_anomalies). Keep output <=20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We previously computed global P95 thresholds per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) and detected anomalies in the incident window (2022-03-21 11:00–11:30 CST). The top anomaly groups (up to 20 shown) are short-lived (mostly 1–2 minutes) and concentrate on adservice KPI series and a mesh metric from shippingservice2-0. Earliest anomaly timestamps from the shown groups include ~11:02, 11:04, 11:07, 11:11, 11:16, 11:27–11:28. However, to identify two distinct failures we need to see whether anomalies cluster at two specific minutes (i.e., many groups first become anomalous at the same minute), which would indicate two failure events. The next step is to aggregate anomaly occurrences by their earliest anomaly minute and inspect the top timestamps and which components contributed at those times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Recompute anomalies as before: load metric.csv, compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full series, then filter metric rows to 2022-03-21 11:00:00 CST through 2022-03-21 11:30:00 CST (inclusive) and mark points where value > group P95. For each group that has any anomaly in the window, find the earliest_anomaly_timestamp. Then: 1) produce a table of counts of groups by earliest_anomaly_timestamp (columns: earliest_anomaly_timestamp, group_count), ordered by group_count desc, top 20 rows; 2) for the top 2 earliest_anomaly_timestamp values, produce a breakdown of affected cmdb_id counts (columns: earliest_anomaly_timestamp, cmdb_id, groups_at_timestamp) ordered by groups_at_timestamp desc, limited to top 20 rows per timestamp. Keep outputs compact and <=20 rows per table." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis found two clear anomaly peaks inside 11:00–11:30 CST: a broad multi-service latency/traffic spike around 11:11 (many trace groups, implicating frontend→adservice and checkout↔shipping paths) and a smaller, localized anomaly at 11:28 (checkoutservice-2 <-> currencyservice-1 row_count traces). Metrics also show cluster peaks at the same minutes (11:11 and 11:28) across many component-KPIs. To finalize root-cause localization for each failure we need corroborating evidence from logs/error logs to (1) confirm which component is actually failing (must be a FAULTY component identified by metrics) and (2) identify the underlying reason (e.g., errors, HTTP 500s, application exceptions, or resource issues reported in logs). The next atomic step is to inspect error_logs.csv for per-minute spikes and per-component message distribution, and to inspect log.csv for any non-zero log.error_count occurrences in the incident window.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) Load error_logs.csv and restrict to 2022-03-21 11:00:00 CST through 2022-03-21 11:30:00 CST (inclusive). Produce a compact table of the top 10 minutes (timestamp) by error_log count in that window (columns: timestamp, total_count). For each of those top minutes, also show the top cmdb_id (component) that contributed the most messages at that minute and its count (columns: timestamp, total_count, top_cmdb_id, top_cmdb_id_count). 2) Load log.csv and filter rows in the same window where log_name == 'log.error_count' and value > 0. Return: (a) up to top 20 rows ordered by value desc with columns (timestamp, cmdb_id, log_name, value); (b) an aggregate table of counts of non-zero log.error_count occurrences per cmdb_id with the earliest timestamp when value>0 (columns: cmdb_id, nonzero_count, earliest_nonzero_timestamp), ordered by nonzero_count desc and limited to top 20. Keep all outputs compact (<=20 rows per table)."
}

